{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Ribonuclease HII is involved in the degradation of the ribonucleotide moiety on RNA-DNA hybrid molecules carrying out endonucleolytic cleavage to 5'-phospo-monoester [[cite:PUB00081182], [cite:PUB00021793]]. This entry is specific for ribonuclease HII.   Several bacteria, such as Bacillus subtilis, have two different type II RNases H, RNases HII and HIII [[cite:PUB00004477]]; double deletion of these leads to cellular lethality. It appears that type I and type II RNases H also have overlapping functions in cells, as over-expression of Escherichia coli RNase HII can complement an RNase HI deletion phenotype [[cite:PUB00056173]]. In Leishmania mitochondria, of the four distinct RNase H genes (H1, HIIA, HIIB, HIIC), HIIC is essential for the survival of the parasite and thus can be a potential target for anti-leishmanial chemotherapy [[cite:PUB00081181]]. Ribonuclease H (RNase H) is classified into two families, type I (prokaryotic RNase HI, eukaryotic RNase H1 and viral RNase H) and type II (prokaryotic RNase HII and HIII, and eukaryotic RNase H2). RNase H endonucleolytically hydrolyzes an RNA strand when it is annealed to a complementary DNA strand in the presence of divalent cations, in DNA replication and repair [[cite:PUB00079405]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "3o3f", "name" "T. maritima RNase H2 D107N in complex with nucleic acid substrate and magnesium ions"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036397", "name" "Ribonuclease H superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"} {"accession" "IPR012337", "name" "Ribonuclease H-like superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"cdd" {"cd07182" "Bacterial Ribonuclease HII-like"}, "hamap" {"MF_00052_B" "Ribonuclease HII [rnhB]"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Ribonuclease HII", "short" "RNase_HII"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counte